ce:section.ce:para:
It is clear that the operating state of this fluorescent switch depends on the redox state of this system. When the system is at oxidation state, the operating state is “on” and it is “off” conversely. Therefore, there are lots of oxidants and reductants which may be used in this switch. However, the experimental data indicate that other reductants or oxidants (such as: citric acid, NaBH4, N2H4, aniline, Na2S2O4, Na2SO3 and KMnO4, NaClO, (NH4)2S2O8, O2, K2Cr2O7, HNO3) cannot control this fluorescent switch system via a reversible progress (Fig. 5
                        ). The strong oxidants/reductants like HNO3 can denature Hb or even damage the PdAP (Fig. S10 and S11). However, the weak ones can not trigger this switch. Therefore, VC/H2O2 is the most appropriate reductant/oxidant to change the operating states of this fluorescent switch system. The absolute quantum yield (Φf
                        ) of the switch system in different operating state is shown in Table 1
                        . Moreover, the anti-interference and stability of this fluorescence switching system are shown in Fig. S12–14.

Fig. 10
 shows the molecular configurations and electric cloud distribution of HOMO–LUMO of all molecules. It is clear that, the catalytic oxidation extends the PdAP planarity. However, there is an obvious angle between the planes of the adjacent pyridine ring planes in PdAP when it is reduced (Scheme 1
). The phenazine skeletons of oxidized PdAP limit the rotation of pyridine ring and improved the rigidity of PdAP [55–62,79–81]. What is more, the π electron cloud is well delocalized in the whole molecular plane of the oxidized PdAP, while it is only well delocalized in the separated pyridine rings of reduced PdAP. This indicated that the molecular structure of oxidized PdAP NPs is more stable have better conjugacy than reduced PdAP NPs, which ensured the FRET procedure proceed efficiently.
